# Data Schema Rules

## Canonical Reference

`scripts/statsgate.proto` is the **definitive reference** for the raw data schema. All documentation, rules, and pipeline code must match it. See `DEVELOPER_GUIDE.md` Section 2 for full field tables and JSON structure examples.

## Protobuf Events

Event types in `StatEvent.event_type` oneof:

| Field # | Type | Key Fields |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | `BulletInit` | tick, shooter (uint64 Steam64), ordnance_odf |
| 2 | `BulletHit` | tick, shooter (uint64 Steam64), ordnance_odf, victim (uint64 Steam64), victim_odf, shooter_odf |
| 3 | `DamageDealt` | tick, shooter (uint64 Steam64), team (int32 slot), ordnance_odf, amount |
| 4 | `DamageReceived` | tick, victim (uint64 Steam64), team (int32 slot), ordnance_odf, amount |
| 5 | `UpdateTick` | tick, repeated PlayerState (Steam64, position, speed, health, ammo, odf, has_target) |
| 6 | `UnitDestroyed` | tick, killer/victim Steam64, killer/victim team slot, killer/victim odf |
| 7 | `UnitSniped` | tick, shooter/victim Steam64, shooter/victim team slot, shooter/victim odf (Phase 3 added the shooter/victim/odf fields; pre-Phase-3 sessions only carry `tick`). **Collector-bug erratum (Phase 3 through ~2026-05-04):** `shooter` Steam64 was overwritten with the victim's Steam64 and `victim` Steam64 was always `0` (typo at `statsgate/statsgate/src/stat_client.cpp:273`). The pipeline ignores both wire Steam64 fields and slot-derives identity from `shooter_team` / `victim_team` via `header.teamnum_to_s64`; this works under both buggy and fixed collectors. See [`docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md`](mdc:docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md#unitsniped) and [`_sniper_investigation/DIAGNOSIS.txt`](mdc:_sniper_investigation/DIAGNOSIS.txt). |
| 8 | `PickupPowerup` | tick, picker (uint64 Steam64), picker_team, picker_odf, powerup_team, powerup_odf (Phase 3 added) |

## Player Identity

Players are identified by `uint64` Steam64 IDs. The header provides three lookup maps:
- `s64_to_nick` — Steam64 → display name
- `teamnum_to_s64` — slot (1-10) → Steam64
- `s64_to_teamnum` — Steam64 → slot (reverse of above)

## Critical: Damage Semantics

### The `team` Field

The `team` field is **ALWAYS the owning player's slot number (1-10)**. It is NOT a faction ID. Faction is determined by slot convention: 1-5 = Team 1, 6-10 = Team 2.

### Adjacent Pair Rule

`DamageDealt` and `DamageReceived` events are **ALWAYS adjacent pairs**. Both have identical `amount` values (`dmg.value` in the engine). Consume both together.

### Attribution Logic

- `dd.team == 0` or `dd.amount == 0.0` → skip **shooter attribution only**; victim received damage from paired DR is still processed
- `dr.team == 0` → skip victim attribution (world prop victim)
- `shooter > 0` → **personal** dealt credit to that player
- `shooter == 0` → **asset** dealt credit to the owning slot (from `team` field)
- `victim > 0` → **personal** received credit to that player
- `victim == 0` → **asset** received credit to the owning slot (from `team` field)
- Both `shooter > 0` AND `victim > 0` (and shooter not skipped) → **rivalry matrix**

### Derived Leaderboard Fields (PvP/PvE Split)

The pipeline adds four derived fields to each `leaderboard[].personal` entry, decomposing `dealt` / `received` into human-vs-human and human-vs-non-player components:

- `pvp_dealt` = `sum(rivalry[s64].values())` — player-on-player subset (shooter > 0 AND victim > 0). Includes friendly-fire between humans.
- `pve_dealt` = `dealt − pvp_dealt` — damage to AI units + world props (single combined bucket).
- `pvp_received` = column sum of `rivalry[*][s64]` — damage received from humans.
- `pve_received` = `received − pvp_received` — damage received from AI units / world.

Each is rounded independently to 1 decimal, so `pvp + pve` may differ from the combined `dealt`/`received` by up to ±0.1. The same split is mirrored at the faction level in `faction_totals[n].{pvp_dealt, pve_dealt, pvp_received, pve_received}` and at the career level in the All Matches aggregate's `career_stats[].{total_pvp_dealt, total_pve_dealt, total_pvp_received, total_pve_received}` (built client-side from `match_contributions.json` by `js/all-matches-aggregator.js`).

### Structure Damage Attribution (v2.2 addition)

`leaderboard[].personal.structure_dealt` is the share of a player's `dealt` that landed on **enemy buildings**. `DamageDealt` carries no `victim_odf` in the proto — only `BulletHit` does — so the pipeline maintains a per-`(tick, shooter, ordnance)` FIFO of `BulletHit.victim_odf` values and popleft's the queue when the paired `DamageDealt` arrives. A pop is credited to `structure_dealt` when (a) the victim ODF is in the `Building` category of `data/odf.min.json` and (b) the victim's faction-code (i/e/f from the ODF prefix) differs from the shooter's team faction. Mirror matches (both teams the same faction) fall back to crediting all damage because the faction filter can't distinguish own vs enemy buildings; matches where the shooter's team faction can't be resolved likewise skip the filter (honesty over silent drops). Implementation: `_load_building_odfs()` + `bh_pending` + `player_structure_dealt_by_vfc` in `scripts/process_stats.py`. Propagated into `match_contributions.json` per `_extract_contribution()` so the All Matches aggregator carries it through.

In v2.3, `structure_dealt` is no longer a primary VTSR-T axis (v2.2's `structure_share` was broadened to the larger `pve_share`, which sums all enemy non-human damage from `personal.pve_dealt`). `structure_dealt` is still emitted for the dashboard's per-match leaderboard column AND consumed by `scripts/elo.py` to subtract from `thug_efficiency`'s denominator (so structure damage flows entirely to `pve_share` rather than diluting the dogfight efficiency score).

### v2.3 PvP/PvE leaderboard fields (new in match.schema_version 4)

Each `leaderboard[].personal` row gains six new fields supplementing the existing `pvp_dealt`/`pve_dealt`/etc. damage split:

- `pvp_kills`: kills against other human players (sum of `kill_rivalry[s64].values()` — events with both killer and victim being Steam64 players)
- `pve_kills`: `kills - pvp_kills`, never negative (kills against AI / world)
- `pvp_deaths`: deaths from other human players (column sum of `kill_rivalry[*][s64]`)
- `pve_deaths`: `deaths - pvp_deaths`, never negative
- `pvp_shots_hit`: subset of `shots_hit` where the BulletHit's victim was a Steam64 player. Drives the per-weapon `weapon_breakdown[w].pvp_hits` field.
- `pvp_accuracy`: `pvp_shots_hit / max(1, shots_fired)`. Subset of `accuracy`.

Each weapon entry on `weapon_breakdown` also gains `pvp_hits` (subset of `hits`). Together these power the v2.3 thug ELO axes (`thug_kill_rate` blends pvp + α·pve; `thug_accuracy` is weapon-normalized using the per-weapon pvp_hits) and the dashboard's `TOTAL (PvP/PvE)` chip rendering.

### Loadout Profile + Per-Ship Combat (v2.3 addition)

Each `leaderboard[]` row gains two new sibling blocks:

- `loadout`: `{ships, primary_ship, secondary_ship, ship_diversity, active_seconds}`. Per-ship time distribution sourced from per-tick `update_tick.players[].odf` samples in `scripts/process_stats.py`. Each entry in `ships[odf_lower] = {name, share, seconds}` carries a pre-resolved pretty name (`Tank`, `Scout`, `Assault Tank`, `Pilot`, etc.) via the same `prettify_odf()` chain (`unit_name(odf)` → stripped-VSR → `wpn_name(odf)` → title-cased stem) that resolves weapons elsewhere. `primary_ship` / `secondary_ship` are records of `{odf, name, share}` (not bare strings) so consumers don't have to re-resolve. **No class taxonomy** — consumers see actual ships, not invented bucket labels.
- `per_ship_combat`: list of `{ship, ship_name, time_seconds, kills, deaths, pvp_kills, pvp_deaths, pve_kills, pve_deaths, dealt, shots, hits, pvp_hits, accuracy, pvp_accuracy, dpm, kd}` rows, one per ship with time>0, sorted by time desc. Tick-joined to active ship at event time via the running `s64_to_current_odf` map (cold-start: events before the player's first `update_tick` bucket to ship `"unknown"`).

Display-only — no axis math reads these blocks. Career-rolled by `js/all-matches-aggregator.js` into `career_loadout` + `career_per_ship_combat` on each `career_stats[]` row (cached `ship_names[odf]` map populated on first encounter so the rollup emits names without re-resolving).

### Source-Level Filters

These are applied by the statsgate collector before data reaches us:
- Collision damage (`DAMAGE_TYPE_COLLISION`) is excluded at source — never in data
- `ordnance_odf` can be null (water/environmental damage) — display as "Unknown"
- BulletInit/BulletHit only recorded for recognized players (in `s64_to_nick`)

### Sentinel Damage Filter

The pipeline drops `DamageDealt` / `DamageReceived` events whose `amount > 1e6`. These are engine-emitted sentinels from the BZCC `DAMAGE_TYPE_UNKNOWN` force-kill pathway (observed value: `268,435,456.0` = `2^28`), not real combat. The guard is applied at the top of the `damage_dealt` branch and the timeline recompute loop in `scripts/process_stats.py` before any accumulator touches the amount. Both the DD and its paired DR are consumed together. Per-match telemetry lives on `match.sentinel_damage = { count, total_amount, first_tick, last_tick }` (counts **pairs**, not individual events); aggregate rollup at `meta.total_sentinel_damage_dropped` + `meta.matches_with_sentinel_damage`. All match-global / always-unfiltered. The Raw Browser Reconcile view mirrors this filter (same helper constant, inline pill surfaces the literal dropped total); the raw events table still displays sentinel values verbatim. Full evidence chain + decompile + struct layout: [§7 Sentinel Damage Filter in docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md](../../docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md#7-sentinel-damage-filter).

### Faction Determination

Faction is determined purely by slot convention: slots 1-5 = Team 1, slots 6-10 = Team 2. The `slot_to_faction()` function in the pipeline encodes this.

### Team Faction Detection (ISDF / Hadean / Scion)

Slot membership tells you which team a player is on, but not which **faction** that team picked at lobby. The pipeline derives faction labels (ISDF / Hadean / Scion) from per-slot ODF signals via two complementary algorithms — **Algorithm A** (starting ship: first non-empty `PlayerState.odf` per slot) and **Algorithm B** (event-stream votes: first-letter votes from every team-attributed vehicle/structure/pilot ODF the slot's owner emitted across `BulletHit`, `UnitDestroyed`, `UpdateTick`, `PickupPowerup`, `UnitSniped`). The combined per-slot vote determines each slot's faction; the per-team mode determines the team's faction.

Constants in `scripts/process_stats.py`:
- `RECYCLER_ODFS` / `FACTORY_ODFS` — recycler + factory ODFs grouped by faction (used by faction detection's documentation + `compute_match_winner()`).
- `FACTION_BY_PREFIX = {"i": "ISDF", "e": "Hadean", "f": "Scion"}` — first-letter -> faction name. Reliable for vehicles/structures/pilots, NOT for weapon ordnance or generic deployables.
- `PILOT_ODFS` — `is*_m` / `es*_m` / `fs*_m` pilot variants used for the kill-feed Self/World fallback.
- `faction_from_odf(odf)` — returns the faction code (`'i'` / `'e'` / `'f'`) or `None` for empty/unrecognized ODFs. Vote sources call this on every team-attributed unit ODF.
- `detect_team_factions(slot_first_odf, slot_faction_votes)` — combines A + B and returns `{1: {"code", "name"} | None, 2: {"code", "name"} | None}`.

Output: `match.team_factions` (sibling to `team_leaders`). Match-global, always-unfiltered. Schema v3+. Pre-v3 matches simply have no block (UI hides the badge). Full per-source vote table + edge-case notes: [§9 Team Faction Detection in docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md](../../docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md#9-team-faction-detection).

### Match Winner Inference

`compute_match_winner(kill_feed)` in `scripts/process_stats.py` derives `match.winner` from the cleaned kill feed via a **toggle model** on recycler/factory destruction events: each destruction toggles a "dead" state per team, and the parity at match end determines whether that team's rec/fac is dead or rebuilt-alive. Outcomes classify as `clean_win` (one team fully dead, other untouched), `contested` (both teams fully dead, tie-broken by who fell first), or `unclear` (rebuild ambiguity, premature quit, timeout, or commander self-demolition that didn't register cleanly). Output is always emitted as `match.winner = {team, loser, decided_at_tick, decided_by, evidence}`; `team` / `loser` are `null` for unclear. Match-global, always-unfiltered — the renderer must read from `currentData.match.winner` rather than scanning the (filterable) `kills.feed`. Full toggle-model rationale + edge cases: [§10 Match Winner Inference in docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md](../../docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md#10-match-winner-inference).

### UnitDestroyed Four-Way Classification (Phase 3)

Every `UnitDestroyed` event is routed into one of four buckets at the top of the `unit_destroyed` branch in `scripts/process_stats.py`, **before any kill / vehicle-destruction accumulator touches the event**:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
  Start[unit_destroyed event] --> InDep{victim_odf in<br/>KNOWN_DEPLOYABLE_ODFS?}
  InDep -- yes --> Dep[deployable_destructions block<br/>SKIP all kill aggregations]
  InDep -- no --> InPow{victim_odf in<br/>KNOWN_POWERUP_ODFS?}
  InPow -- no --> Vehicle[Real vehicle<br/>FLOW THROUGH to existing<br/>kills accumulators]
  InPow -- yes --> KT{killer_team == 0?}
  KT -- yes --> Pickup[Powerup pickup<br/>SKIP. New-schema gets<br/>rich pickup_powerup data]
  KT -- no --> Destruction[powerup_destructions block<br/>SKIP all kill aggregations]
```

| Bucket | `kills.*` impact | New JSON block | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Real vehicle | full passthrough | none | Existing `player_kills`, `kill_feed`, `vehicle_destruction_count`, `kill_rivalry` accumulators |
| Powerup pickup | suppressed | `pickups.feed` (new-schema only, populated from real `PickupPowerup` events) | Synthetic `unit_destroyed` companion silently dropped; engine continues to double-emit even in new-schema sessions |
| Powerup/crate destruction | suppressed | `powerup_destructions.{feed, by_player, by_odf, totals}` | Real player shot the powerup before pickup, effectively denying the enemy economy |
| Deployable destruction | suppressed | `deployable_destructions.{by_player, by_odf, totals}` | No `feed` (too noisy); mines self-detonate, expire, or get shot |

Two pipeline classification sets drive the routing:
- **Powerups (DB-derived)**: built per-pipeline-run by `_load_known_powerup_odfs(odf_db)` from the `Powerup` bucket of `data/odf.min.json` (currently 159 entries) PLUS synthesized `*vsr.odf` and `*_vsr.odf` variants for every entry (covering VSR-mod ODFs that inherit from stock parents at runtime). Threaded into `process_match()` as a `known_powerup_odfs` parameter (symmetric with `resolve_weapon` / `resolve_unit`). The DB is the source of truth; if a powerup is missing, extend `data/odf.min.json` upstream.
- `KNOWN_DEPLOYABLE_ODFS` (1 entry: `fball2c.odf`): ground-deployed utilities. Hand-curated by domain knowledge despite the high (79%) team-zero rate that would otherwise misroute them as powerups; absent from the DB Powerup bucket.

`powerup_display_name(odf)` is a closure inside `process_match` that resolves powerup ODFs through `unit_name` -> stripped-vsr `unit_name` -> `wpn_name` -> stripped-vsr `wpn_name` -> title-cased stem fallback, suffixed with " Powerup" to disambiguate from the same-named weapon ordnance. Used by `pickups.feed[].powerup_name`, `pickups.by_odf[].name`, `powerup_destructions.feed[].powerup_name`, and `powerup_destructions.by_odf[].name`. The dominant case is `apserv_vsr.odf` (110,589 pickup events in the corpus): not in the Powerup bucket directly, but `_strip_vsr_suffix` resolves it via `apserv.odf` -> "Service Pod" -> "Service Pod Powerup".

`apserv_vsr.odf` stays in the legacy chart-only `VEHICLE_DESTRUCTION_IGNORE_ODFS` to suppress the residual ~13% of real-combat service-pod destructions from the Vehicle Destruction Breakdown chart only (those events still flow into `powerup_destructions.feed`).

Audit script `scripts/audit_pickup_powerup.mjs` reads the same `data/odf.min.json` and verifies coverage; "promotion candidates" surface ODFs the DB is missing entries for. **Domain knowledge is required** when extending the deployable set — do NOT auto-promote based on team-zero % alone (the `fball2c` precedent). Full evidence chain + maintenance procedure: [§8 UnitDestroyed Classification & Powerup Economy in docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md](../../docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md#8-unitdestroyed-classification-powerup-economy).

## ODF Weapon Name Resolution

Resolution chain (first match wins):
1. `WeaponClass.ordName` → `wpnName`
2. `DispenserClass.objectClass` → `wpnName`
3. `TargetingGunClass.leaderName` → `wpnName`
4. Explosion mapping (Vehicle → TorpedoClass/GameObjectClass → parent weapon)
5. **Fallback**: raw ODF string minus `.odf` extension
6. **Null ordnance**: `"Unknown"`

Disambiguate collisions by appending raw ODF in parentheses.

## Pipeline Output

Pre-computed JSON in `data/processed/`. See `DEVELOPER_GUIDE.md` Section 5 for full JSON structure with examples.

- `matches.json` — manifest (includes `submitter`, `has_position_data`, `has_target_lock_data`, `has_pickup_data` fields per match)
- `<match_id>.json` — per-match: `match` (with `has_position_data`, `has_target_lock_data`, `has_pickup_data`, `team_leaders`, **`team_factions`**, `schema_version`), `leaderboard` (with kills/deaths/hit_targets), `faction_totals`, `rivalry_matrix`, `top_rivalries`, `weapon_meta`, **`odf_map`**, `timeline`, `asset_damage`, `kills` (leaderboard/feed/by_vehicle/kill_rivalry_matrix; `feed[]` carries `killer_team` + `victim_team` raw slot ints), `pickups` (Phase 3: feed/by_player/by_odf/totals/has_pickup_data), `powerup_destructions` (Phase 3: feed/by_player/by_odf/totals — destruction stats), `deployable_destructions` (Phase 3: by_player/by_odf/totals — no feed), `snipes` (Phase 3: feed/by_player/totals), `positioning`, **`highlights`** (schema_version 2: fixed-slate 12-card award catalog — match-global + always-unfiltered; cards self-omit when their data gates fail). `match.schema_version` is `1` for Phase 3 baseline, `2` once `highlights` shipped, `3` once `team_factions` + `winner` ship; absence means legacy data.
- `match_contributions.json` — slim per-match contributions for the All Matches aggregator. Dict keyed by `<match_id>.json`; each entry holds the fields needed to rebuild career stats / global weapon meta / global rivalries: `id`, `map`, `date`, `duration_sec`, `submitter`, `player_count`, `has_position_data`, `has_target_lock_data`, `has_pickup_data`, `sentinel_damage_count`, **`team_leaders`**, **`team_factions`**, **`winner`** (`{team, decided_by}`), **`snipes_by_player`**, **`powerup_destructions_by_player`**, plus per-player `leaderboard` (flat damage / shot / kill / weapon-breakdown / positioning fields, **`steam64`**, **`slot`**, **`team`**, **`is_commander`**), `weapon_meta`, and `rivalry_matrix`. Built by `_extract_contribution()` in `scripts/process_stats.py`. Consumed by [`js/all-matches-aggregator.js`](../../js/all-matches-aggregator.js) which sums it over the picker-filtered subset of file ids and produces the legacy shape (`{meta, career_stats, global_weapon_meta, global_rivalries}`) plus three new top-level blocks: **`commander_stats`** (rows + head-to-head + most-commanded-against), **`faction_stats`** (per-team-slot picks + per-faction win counts), **`meta_charts`** (maps / duration bands / player counts / submitters / matches over time), and **`career_highlights`** (24-card highlight grid built by `buildCareerHighlightsInline()`). DEPRECATED → DELETED: `all_matches.json` is no longer written by the pipeline; the legacy `build_all_matches_aggregate()` Python function remains as reference code only. **PIPELINE_VERSION** bumped from 6 to 7 in this overhaul (the contribution shape change forced one full reprocess).
- `elo_current.json` — per-player ratings emitted by `scripts/elo.py`. Schema (v4): `{schema_version, alpha, alpha_pve, anchor, rating_scale, expected_score_logistic_scale, k_loss_aversion, rating_floor, floor_taper_window, k_base, k_floor, provisional_prior, provisional_threshold, min_player_count, min_duration_sec, computed_at, match_count, matches_excluded_low_player_count, matches_excluded_short_duration, matches_excluded_no_winner, weights, ratings[]}`. The `weights` block carries **8 keys** as of v2.3 (`net_damage_share`, `thug_kill_rate`, `thug_efficiency`, `thug_accuracy`, `pve_share`, `mobility`, `snipe_bonus`, `target_lock_pct`). Per-row `ratings[i]` carries `{name, steam64, vtsr, thug_elo, wins_elo, matches_played, matches_provisional, last_match_id, last_delta, peak_vtsr, peak_at, win_history, axis_means}`. Full algorithm: see `DEVELOPER_GUIDE.md` §13. **Corpus-wide / picker-filter-unaware** per `filter-contract.mdc`. **v2.3 (current)**: alpha-blended thug composite + Combat ELO → Thug ELO rename. Three changes: (1) `thug_kill_rate`/`thug_accuracy`/`thug_efficiency` credit PvE work at fractional weight `ALPHA_PVE = 0.5` (locked default, surfaced as `alpha_pve` in elo_current.json — tunable post-ship without a schema bump). (2) `thug_accuracy` is weapon-normalized against the lobby's per-weapon baseline (replaces flat shots_hit/shots_fired). (3) `pve_share` replaces v2.2's narrower `structure_share` — covers all enemy non-human damage (structures + mobile AI; sources from `personal.pve_dealt`). JSON field rename `combat_elo` → `thug_elo` reflects the architectural Combat ELO → Thug ELO rename (sets up future VTSR-C commander rating). New per-rating `axis_means` block: career-average per-axis z-scores. Powers the VTSR-T leaderboard's "Strong axes" tooltip on the rating cell. `ELO_SCHEMA_VERSION` bumped 3 → 4; `PIPELINE_VERSION` bumped 10 → 11. **Pre-v2.3 `peak_vtsr` values are no longer comparable.**
- `elo_history.json` — per-match ELO deltas (chronological) emitted alongside `elo_current.json`. `{schema_version, history[]}` with each `history[i] = {match_id, match_date, match_excluded, exclusion_reason?, deltas[]}`. Each `deltas[i]` carries `{name, steam64, before, after, delta, performance, expected, axis_contributions}`. The v2 `expected` field is the opponent-strength-weighted `E_i`. The **v2.3** `axis_contributions` field is the per-axis z-score after clip-and-divide-by-2 (range $[-1, +1]$ per axis), keyed by axis name; axes that were unavailable for this lobby (and thus had their weight redistributed) are OMITTED. Audit invariant: $\sum_a z_a \cdot w'_a \approx \text{performance}$. Powers the VTSR-T leaderboard's per-axis breakdown popover on the Last-delta cell.

#### Career-roster threshold (5-match minimum)

`VTAggregate.build()` applies a hard-coded `MIN_CAREER_MATCHES = 5` after summation: any `career_stats[]` row with `matches_played < 5` is dropped, and `global_rivalries[]` is cascade-filtered to the kept names so we never surface a rivalry pointing at a hidden player. `global_weapon_meta` and `meta.{match_count, total_duration_sec, ...}` are untouched — the threshold is exclusively about cross-match player identity. Per-match views (`<match_id>.json` → Player Leaderboard, kill feed, per-match rivalries) are fully unaffected.

The threshold reads `matches_played` *in the current scope*, so a player with 30 career matches who only appears in 3 of the picker-filtered subset is hidden — semantics is "show me players with meaningful presence in this view".

Two output fields surface the threshold so the UI doesn't duplicate the constant:

- `meta.min_career_matches` — live threshold value (currently `5`). UI labels read this instead of hardcoding "5+".
- `meta.players_dropped_by_min_matches` — count of `career_stats[]` rows pruned for the current scope. `0` when nobody was below threshold; the UI suppresses the hidden-count chip in that case.

The Python `build_all_matches_aggregate()` reference code does **not** apply the threshold (it stays the canonical "raw" aggregate); only the JS aggregator prunes. Pipeline-vs-JS parity tests will diverge by exactly the prune step.

### `odf_map` (per-match, match-global)

Top-level object on each per-match JSON. Keys are raw ODF strings exactly as they appear in the binpb wire format (including the `.odf` suffix); values are the best human-readable name. Resolution chain in `prettify_odf`: (1) weapons via `build_weapon_name_resolver` (the `Weapon.*` ordName/objectClass/leaderName/explosion chain), (2) any other game object via `build_unit_name_resolver` (looks up `GameObjectClass.unitName` across every top-level ODF DB category — `Vehicle`, `Building`, `Powerup`, `Pilot`, `Ordnance` — covering deployable pods like `apeburst.odf` → `Burst Gun`, structures like `ibscav_vsr.odf` → `Extractor`, and `_vsr` overrides via direct key lookup against the flattened `data/odf.min.json`), (3) title-cased form of the raw stem as a last-resort fallback for ODFs the DB does not recognize at all. Same-name collisions inside a match (e.g. multiple "Pulse" weapons or stock + `_vsr` "Scavenger") disambiguate as `Name (raw_stem)` via the shared `disambiguate_names` helper. `kills.by_vehicle[].name` is routed through the same `prettify_odf` so it always agrees with `odf_map`. Populated from every `*_odf` field encountered in the match: `BulletInit.ordnance_odf`, `BulletHit.{ordnance_odf, victim_odf, shooter_odf}`, `DamageDealt.ordnance_odf`, `DamageReceived.ordnance_odf`, `UnitDestroyed.{killer_odf, victim_odf}`, and `PlayerState.odf`. Typically 10–50 entries per match. Consumed primarily by the Raw Data Browser (`js/raw-browser.js`) to annotate raw ODF strings inline with their resolved name. **Match-global: always unfiltered** (see `.cursor/rules/filter-contract.mdc`).

## UpdateTick Processing (Positioning)

Axis convention: **+X East, +Y Up, +Z North** (developer-confirmed). Horizontal plane = `(x, z)`; all distance / path / hull math uses `sqrt(dx² + dz²)`. `y` is stored in `trail.y[]` but not consumed by v1 metrics.

Downsample target: **1 Hz** regardless of source `tick_rate`. Keep a sample if `(tick - min_tick) % (tick_rate / 1) == 0` per player (gaps don't drift cadence because each player has its own `last_kept_tick`).

Spawn: **median of first 3 kept samples** per player (robust against tick-0 jitter).

Teleport detection: self-calibrated `max(300, p99_speed × 2)` u/s on horizontal delta only. Teleport gaps excluded from `path_length`, split `trail.segments`, and exclude first re-entry of each new segment from `return_to_base_count`. Teleport ticks still count for `time_in_base_pct`.

`base_separation`: floored internal scaling value `max(computed_centroid_dist, 500, observed_max_range × 0.3)`. Drives `R_base = 0.15 × base_separation` for the `time_in_base_pct` heuristics. **Not** the user-facing "how far apart are the bases" measurement — that is `base_to_base_distance`, the raw unfloored horizontal distance between Team 1 and Team 2 spawn centroids (`null` when either team empty). Both fields are emitted on the positioning block; `base_to_base_distance` is also mirrored onto the `match` object. Personal base radius: team stddev × 1.1 clipped to `[100, 400]`; 150 fallback for unknown/small teams.

`map_bounds`: 2D `{min:{x,z}, max:{x,z}}` reference frame for `heatmap_grid_xz` binning and canvas projections. Sourced from `StatHeader.terrain_*` when the collector populates it (new-schema sessions), otherwise from observed player extents. The choice is surfaced as `positioning.map_bounds_source` (`"terrain"` | `"observed"` | `null`). Full 3D terrain extents `{min:{x,y,z}, max:{x,y,z}}` live on `positioning.terrain_bounds` (mirrored to `match.terrain_bounds`); `null` for pre-schema sessions. Axis convention: +X East, +Y Up, +Z North. All of `map_bounds`, `map_bounds_source`, `terrain_bounds`, `base_separation`, `base_to_base_distance` are match-global / always-unfiltered.

Activity score (0–100, higher = more active / more map coverage): weighted combo of `(1 − time_in_base_pct)` (0.5), `normalized_max_dist` (0.3), and `normalized_path_per_sec` (0.2). Normalizers are **match-relative p95** values (computed across all players in the match), so the score self-calibrates per match. Movement bands are fixed thresholds on `activity_score`: 0-20 Defensive, 21-40 Territorial, 41-60 Balanced, 61-80 Mobile, **81-100 Aggressive**. Because the score is match-relative, cross-match comparisons must go through the `career_stats` aggregates (`mean_movement_score`, `movement_band_dominant`) rather than per-match scores. Returns count requires `>= 5s` outside `R_base × 1.2` before crossing back through `R_base × 0.8` (filters boundary noise). Full derivation and worked example in `docs/DATA_DICTIONARY.md`.

Target lock (T-key) usage: per player, `metrics.target_lock_pct = sum(has_target) / sample_count` — an absolute 0-1 ratio over the kept 1 Hz samples. Match-global availability flag `positioning.has_target_lock_data` (mirrored on `match.has_target_lock_data` and manifest entries) is `true` iff any `PlayerState.has_target=true` sample was observed. Career aggregation: `career_stats[].mean_target_lock_pct` is a valid direct average over matches where the flag is true; denominator exposed as `career_stats[].matches_with_target_lock_data` and `meta.matches_with_target_lock_data`. Unlike `activity_score`, `target_lock_pct` is absolute and cross-match comparable. Rendered on the Player Performance Radar's 8th "T-Key Usage" axis.

Per-match weapon variety (Career Radar per-match scale): `career_stats[].mean_weapons_used` is a **valid direct average** of the per-match `len(weapon_breakdown)` count — like `mean_target_lock_pct`, the underlying per-match value is absolute (independent of match volume), so a straight average is meaningful. Powers axis 6 (Weapon Diversity) of the Career Radar when the user flips the card-header **Per match** toggle; the **Totals** scale uses lifetime `len(career_stats[].weapon_breakdown)` instead. The two volume-biased axes that toggle alongside it (Damage Dealt, Kills) are derived at render time as `total_dealt / matches_played` and `total_kills / matches_played` — no separate `mean_*` field required. Both aggregators (`scripts/process_stats.py` `build_all_matches_aggregate()` and `js/all-matches-aggregator.js` `VTAggregate.build()`) emit `mean_weapons_used` rounded to 1 decimal so output stays byte-identical.

When no `UpdateTick` events present, emit `positioning = { has_position_data: false, players: {}, ... }` and set `match.has_position_data = false`. Manifest entry gets the same flag.

Output files are named by match ID (timestamp-derived, e.g. `2026-04-16T01-27-48.json`). Match display names are derived from `header.map` via prettification (strip `vsr`/`vsrmort`/`vsrstt` prefix/suffix, strip `.bzn`, title-case).

All numeric values pre-rounded (1 decimal for damage, 3 for ratios/accuracy). Ratio is `null` for infinite (dealt > 0, received = 0).

**Client-side filtering note:** When the global player filter is active, `weapon_meta` is recomputed client-side by aggregating `leaderboard[].weapon_breakdown` across the filtered player set. The pre-aggregated `weapon_meta` array is used only for the unfiltered "All Players" view. The `odf` field is unavailable in client-recomputed weapon_meta (no renderer uses it). `kills.by_vehicle` is always unfiltered (match-global, not per-player attributed). See `filter-contract.mdc` for the full filter contract and the checklist that every new output field must satisfy.
